In this question you must show all stages of your working. Solutions relying entirely on calculator technology are not acceptable.

[i is a unit vector due east and j is a unit vector due north. Position vectors are given relative to a fixed origin O.]

At time t seconds, t ≥ 1, the position vector of a particle P is r metres, where

r = ct²i + (1/8)t³j

and c is a constant.

When t = 4, the bearing of P from O is 135°.

(a) Show that c = 3. (3)

(b) Find the speed of P when t = 4. (4)

When t = T, P is accelerating in the direction of (−i − 27j).

(c) Find the value of T. (4)

Question 5 (12 marks)
At time t = 0, a small stone is projected with velocity 35 m s⁻¹ from a point O on horizontal ground at an angle α to the horizontal, where tan α = 3/4.

In an initial model, the stone is modelled as a particle P moving freely under gravity. The stone hits the ground at point A.

For the motion of P from O to A:

at time t seconds, the horizontal distance of P from O is x metres
at time t seconds, the vertical distance of P above the ground is y metres
(a) Show that y = (3/4)x − (1/160)x². (6)

(b) Use the answer to (a), or otherwise, to find the length OA. (2)

Using the model, the greatest height of the stone above the ground is H metres.

(c) Use the answer to (a), or otherwise, to find the value of H. (2)

The model is refined to include air resistance. Using this new model, the greatest height is K metres.

(d) State which is greater, H or K, justifying your answer. (1)

(e) State one limitation of this refined model. (1)

Question 6 (9 marks)
A uniform rod AB of mass M and length 2a.

The rod has its end A on rough horizontal ground
The rod rests in equilibrium against a small smooth fixed horizontal peg P
The point C on the rod, where AC = 1.5a, is the point of contact between the rod and the peg
The rod is at an angle θ to the ground, where tan θ = 4/3
The rod lies in a vertical plane perpendicular to the peg.

The magnitude of the normal reaction of the peg on the rod at C is S.

(a) Show that S = (2/5)Mg. (3)

The coefficient of friction between the rod and the ground is μ.

Given that the rod is in limiting equilibrium,

(b) find the value of μ. (6)

